Exploration of Flight Dataset -"Airline On-Time Performance Data"¶

by Joseph Ebere¶

Introduction¶

The dataset name is "Airline On-Time Performance Data". This dataset reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delay, from 1987 to 1989.

The features of interest in the dataset are;

Actual Arrival Times (ArrTime): is the instance when the pilot sets the aircraft parking brake after arriving at the airport gate or passenger unloading area.

Actual Departure Times (DepTime): is the instance when the pilot releases the aircraft parking brake after passengers have loaded and aircraft doors have been closed.

Arrival Delay (ArrDelay): Arrival delay equals the difference of the actual arrival time minus the scheduled arrival time.

CRS Computer Reservation System. CRS provide information on airline schedules, fares and seat availability to travel agencies and allow agents to book seats and issue tickets.

Cancelled Flight (Cancelled): A flight that was listed in a carrier's computer reservation system during the seven calendar days prior to scheduled departure but was not operated.

Departure Delay (DepDelay): The difference between the scheduled departure time and the actual departure time from the origin airport gate.

Diverted Flight (Diverted): A flight that is required to land at a destination other than the original scheduled destination for reasons beyond the control of the pilot/company.

Elapsed Time (for CRSElapsedTime & ActualElapsedTIme): The time computed from gate departure time to gate arrival time.

Scheduled Departure Time (CSRSDepTime): The scheduled time that an aircraft should lift off from the origin airport.

Scheduled Time Of Arrival (CRSArrTime): The scheduled time that an aircraft should cross a certain point (landing or metering fix).

Unique Carrier (unique): Unique Carrier Code. It is the Carrier Code most recently used by a carrier. A numeric suffix is used to distinguish duplicate codes, for example, PA, PA (1), PA (2). Use this field to perform analysis of data reported by one and only one carrier.

flights = flights.drop(["Year", "Month", "DayofMonth", "TaxiIn", "TaxiOut", "CancellationCode", "TailNum", "FlightNum", "AirTime", "CarrierDelay", "WeatherDelay", "NASDelay", "SecurityDelay", "LateAircraftDelay"], axis=1)

#Rearranging the columns so "Date" will appear first
flights.insert(0, "Date", flights.pop("Date"))

The column "DayOfWeek" contains numeric representation of the days of the week;

1 = Monday, 2 = Tuesday, 3 = Wednesday, 4 = Thursday, 5 = Friday, 6 = Saturday, 7 = Sunday.

Therefore, we will convert these numeric values to the actual days of the week

In [12]:
#Converting the column datatype to str in order to be able to replace the values accordingly
flights[["DayOfWeek", "Cancelled", "Diverted"]] = flights[["DayOfWeek", "Cancelled", "Diverted"]].astype(str)
In [13]:
#Replacing the numeric values with the days of the week
flights["DayOfWeek"] = flights["DayOfWeek"].replace(["1", "2", "3", "4", "5", "6", "7"], ["Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday"])
flights["Cancelled"] = flights["Cancelled"].replace(["0", "1"], ["No", "Yes"])
flights["Diverted"] = flights["Diverted"].replace(["0", "1"], ["No", "Yes"])

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Three years of data were loaded and combined to a single dataframe; "flight", the dataset has 11,555,122 rows and 29 columns(features). After wrangling, where some columns that are irrelevant to the exploration were dropped, the updated structure of the dataset is then; 11,339,313 rows and 16 columns of variables

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I will try to find out the destinations or arrival cities that are home to more delays or cancellations. Also, the preferred times for flights to occur will also be deduced. Similar data from multiple years will be explored to check for changes and concurrent trends.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

From the features of interest, as stated above, we will be much concerned with the features; Cancelled, Diverted, Dest, Origin, ArrDelay, DepDelay, DepTime, ArrTime. The other colummns(variables) in the wrangled dataset will support, though to a lesser proportion.

This shows a yearly reduction in the number of cancellation and can be as a result of improved technology or some other factors that might be deduce later in this exploration.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The feature "Cancelled" was represented with numbers (0 and 1) which does not easily tell us if the flight was cancelled or not.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When investigating the "Cancelled" feature for the three years under consideration (1987, 1988, 1989), a number of issues was observed. Firstly, the corresponding value for Cancellation were given as 0 and 1, representing No and Yes. Also, when the Null (NAN or NA) data were dropped, it actually removed all the rows in which there was a flight cancellation (i.e Cancellation is Yes).

Therefore, to solve this issues, 0 and 1 were replaced with "No" and "Yes" respectively. Dropping of the Null cells was suspended since the feature "Cancelled" is among the main features of investigation.

Observations:¶

The destinations; ORD, ATL, DEN, LAX, SFO; are home to more cancellations and the trend is the same for the three years under consideration.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There was an interesting relationship observed between departure delay (DepDelay) and arrival delay (ArrDelay). The correlation is a positive correlation, in the sense that each of the delay increases as the other increases, and vice versa.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

A rather interesting observation was made on the relationship between the distance and delay (both ArrDelay and DepDelay). Distance does not have any correlation with either of the delays, whether positive or negative correlation. Therefore, it can be seen that delay is independent of distance of flight.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Week days like Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday have a consistent lower level of delays and cancellation across the three days under consideration.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The correlation between the features "UniqueCarrier" and "Cancelled" shows that there was no particular carrier that is prone to delay and cancellation across the three years under consideration.

Conclusions¶

From the exploration the folowing conclussions are reached;

For the feature "Origin", the investigation shows that the origin(Cities): ORD, ATL, DFW, LAX, DEN have the highest frequency of flights going out of them and this trend is the same for the three years under consideration (i.e 1987, 1988, 1989).

For the feature "Dest", which represents the destination cities, the same cities ORD, ATL, DFW, LAX and DEN have the highest frequency of flights arrival, and this trend is the same for the years under consideration (1987, 1988, 1989).

The destinations; ORD, ATL, DEN, LAX, SFO; are home to more cancellations and the trend is the same for the three years under consideration.

Week days like Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday have a consistent lower level of delays and cancellation across the three days under consideration. While Thursday has the highest rate delay for the three years under consideration.
